1.ENCAPSULATION
Instead of allowing direct modification of fields, access is provided through well-defined methods,
 which can apply validation, transformation, or additional logic.

Because of this, the internal representation can change later without affecting other parts of the program,
 reducing tight coupling.
 
 True encapsulation requires the object to maintain authority over how and when its data changes. Otherwise,
 the class becomes a passive data holder rather than a responsible unit of behavior.
 -----------------------------------------------
 🧠 Inheritance
 --------------------------------------
 Inheritance allows a class to reuse properties and behavior from another class.
 Main goals:

✔ reuse code
✔ create hierarchy
✔ enable polymorphism
✔ allow specialization
Child can provide specific behavior.
class Animal {
    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Generic sound");
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    @Override
    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Bark");
    }
	6) Constructor behavior

Parent constructor runs first.
Tight coupling problem 🚩

Child becomes dependent on parent implementation.

If parent changes → child may break.

So inheritance increases coupling.

This is why modern design prefers composition in many cases.
Why composition is powerful ⭐

Because it gives:

✔ flexibility
✔ replaceable parts
✔ lower coupling
✔ easier testing
✔ avoids fragile hierarchies
class Engine {
    void start() {
        System.out.println("Engine started");
    }
}
class Car {

    // HAS-A relationship
    private Engine engine;

    public Car(Engine engine) {
        this.engine = engine;
    }

    public void start() {
        engine.start();  // delegation
    }
}
STATIC IN INHERITANCE 
class Parent {
    static int a = printA();

    static {
        System.out.println("Parent static block");
    }

    static int printA() {
        System.out.println("Parent static variable");
        return 10;
    }
}

class Child extends Parent {
    static int b = printB();

    static {
        System.out.println("Child static block");
    }

    static int printB() {
        System.out.println("Child static variable");
        return 20;
    }
}
IF we create an object of the child 
now the out put is :
Parent static variable
Parent static block
Child static variable
Child static block
Why parent first?
Because parent must be loaded before child.
------------------------------------
🔥 What Is a Constructor?
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
A constructor is a special method used to initialize a new object when it is created.

It runs automatically when you use new.

It has:

Same name as class

No return type (not even void)
🧠 What Does a Constructor Actually Do?

Three main things:
Initializes object state (assign values)
Enforces mandatory dependencies
Ensures object is valid immediately after creation
It does NOT:
Allocate memory (JVM does that)
Return the object (JVM handles it)
It only initializes.
🔥 Important Rule (Memorize This)

If parent has only parameterized constructors,
child must explicitly call one of them using super(args).

class A {
    A() {
        show();
    }

    void show() {
        System.out.println("A");
    }
}

class B extends A {
    int x = 10;

    void show() {
        System.out.println(x);
    }
}
What prints when:

new B(); see here it prints the x becuase if we create an object of B first call the parent constructor
but it we are calling the same method inside the constructor 
show() is overridden in B.

So dynamic dispatch applies.

Even though we are inside parent constructor,
the actual object is B. 
B.show()
----------------------------------
🔹 final Keyword
----------------------------------
final means: cannot be changed.

It can apply to:

1️⃣ Variable

Value cannot be reassigned.
Why Make a Method Final?

To:

Prevent overriding

Preserve behavior

Ensure security

Avoid broken polymorphism

Example:
If you don’t want subclasses modifying critical logic.
------------------
ABSTRACT METHOD 
-------------------------------
No body

Must be implemented by concrete subclass

Important Rules

Abstract class can have:

Concrete methods

Abstract methods

Constructors

Variables

If a class has even one abstract method → class must be abstract.

Abstract method cannot be:

private

final

static

Because:

private → cannot override

final → cannot override

static → not polymorphic
------------------------------------
⚖ final vs abstract
final	                          abstract
Prevents inheritance	        Requires inheritance
Prevents overriding	            Requires overriding
Complete behavior	            Incomplete behavior
---------------------------------
Interface in Java
What is an Interface?

An interface is a contract — it tells what a class should do, not how to do it.
Questions
👉 Why interface?
To achieve abstraction
To support multiple inheritance
To create loosely coupled code

👉 Can we create object of interface? ❌ No
👉 Can interface have constructor?❌ No
2. Default Methods (Java 8+)
Why introduced?
Before Java 8, adding a method to an interface would break all implementing classes.
Defined using default keyword
Have method body
Can be overridden

interface A {
    default void show() { System.out.println("A"); }
}

interface B {
    default void show() { System.out.println("B"); }
}

class Test implements A, B {
    public void show() {
        A.super.show(); // must resolve conflict
    }
}
 in the above code Test implement A and B both have default method so we must override this show but 
 if Test impleemnt only A means not compulsary to override that default show method 
 👉 Why default method?
To provide backward compatibility
👉 Can default methods be overridden?
✅ Yes

3. Abstract Class vs Interface

This is a VERY IMPORTANT interview question 🔥

Feature	                    Abstract Class	                            Interface
Methods	                  Abstract + Concrete	                 Abstract + Default + Static
Variables	             Can have instance variables	             Only constants
Constructor	                    ✅ Yes	                                  ❌ No
Multiple Inheritance	        ❌ No	                                  ✅ Yes
Access Modifiers	              Any	                                Mostly public
Performance	                 Faster (slightly)	                       Slight overhead

When to Use?
👉 Use Interface when:
You want multiple inheritance
You define a contract

👉 Use Abstract Class when:
You want common code
You need state (instance variables)

-----------
1️⃣ What is Concurrency?
Definition
Concurrency means:
Multiple tasks making progress at the same time.

In Java, concurrency is achieved using threads.
🔥 PART 1 — What is Multithreading?
-----------------------------------------
Multithreading = Multiple threads executing inside the same process.

A thread is a lightweight unit of execution.

✅ Method 1: Extend Thread
✅ Method 2 (Preferred): Implement Runnable

In Java multithreading, both extends Thread and implements Runnable are correct, 
but in industry practice, implements Runnable is preferred in most cases.


✅ 2️⃣ Implementing Runnable (Preferred
You can still extend another class
Better separation of task and thread
More flexible
Works well with thread pools and Executor framework
Industry standard approach
✅ What is a Race Condition in Java?

A race condition happens when:

🔥 Two or more threads access shared data at the same time, and the final result depends on the order in which they execute.


🛡 2️⃣ What is Thread Safety?
✅ Definition:
A class or method is thread-safe if:
It works correctly even when multiple threads access it at the same time.
That means:
No data corruption
No inconsistent state
No unexpected behavior
💡 How to Achieve Thread Safety
synchronized
Locks (ReentrantLock)
Atomic classes
Immutable objects
Concurrent collections
EXAMPLE:synchronized void increment() {
    count++;
}

2️⃣ What is a Race Condition?
--------------
Definition
A race condition occurs when:
Two or more threads access shared data simultaneously and the final result depends on the timing of execution.

so how to fix this race condition 
3️⃣ Fix Using synchronized
What is synchronized?
--------------------
synchronized ensures:
Only one thread can enter the critical section at a time.
5️⃣ Lock (Explicit Lock)
-------------------------
Java provides advanced locking via:ReentrantLock
How it works:
You manually call lock()
You must manually call unlock()
Usually placed in finally block to avoid bugs

🔥 Key Difference Summary
Feature	                  synchronized	     Lock
Automatic release	         ✅ Yes	         ❌ No
Manual unlock	             ❌ No	         ✅ Yes
Try without waiting	         ❌ No	         ✅ Yes
Timeout	                     ❌ No	         ✅ Yes
Interruptible wait	         ❌ No	         ✅ Yes
Fairness option	             ❌ No	         ✅ Yes
Simpler to use	             ✅ Yes	         ❌ Slightly complex

Important Concept******
-----------------------
synchronized is block-level locking
Lock is object-level explicit locking
But internally, both use similar JVM monitor mechanisms — Lock just gives you more control.

⚡ 3️⃣ What is volatile in Java?
----------------------------------------------
✅ Definition:
volatile is a keyword that ensures:
Changes made by one thread to a variable are immediately visible to other threads.

🔥 When To Use volatile

Use it when:
One thread writes
Other threads only read
No compound operations (like ++, +=)

What Is ExecutorService?
--------------------------------------
Instead of manually creating threads: new Thread(() -> {}).start();
🔹 What It Does

ExecutorService:
Manages a pool of threads
Reuses threads
Controls number of threads
Makes concurrency easier

❌ Don’t use new Thread().start() repeatedly
✅ Use a thread pool (ExecutorService) to manage threads













